    <h1>A Brief History of Hangman</h1>

    <p>
        Hangman is a classic word‑guessing game that likely originated in the Victorian era.
        The earliest known version appeared in the late 1800s under the name <em>“Birds, Beasts, and Fishes.”</em>
        In that version, players guessed letters to identify a category-based word, and each wrong guess
        brought the player closer to losing.
    </p>

    <p>
        The modern form of Hangman—using a drawing of a stick figure being completed with each incorrect guess—
        became popular in the early 20th century. It spread widely because it required no special equipment:
        just paper, a pencil, and a good vocabulary.
    </p>

    <p>
        Today, Hangman remains a staple in classrooms, puzzle books, and digital games. Its simple rules,
        quick rounds, and mix of logic and luck have helped it stay popular for more than a century.
    </p>

